Replication

Set up

Results we want to replicate

Fetzer (2019) implemented the following pooled difference-in-difference equation:

\[y_{i,r,t} = \alpha_{i} + \beta_{r,t} + \gamma \times \mathbb{1}(Year>2010) \times Austerity_{i} + \epsilon_{i,r,t}\]

where:

  • \(y_{i,r,t}\) denotes UKIP vote share in council elections of district \(i\), in region \(r\), at time \(t\)

  • \(\alpha_i\) is a fixed effect that absorbs any time-invariant differences in political preferences or sentiment across districts

  • \(\beta_{r,t}\) are region-by-time fixed effects that capture nonlinear time trends specific to each of the 11 regions across the United Kingdom

  • \(\gamma\) measures the effect of the austerity incidence at the district level on the support for UKIP after 2010

The results we are about to replicate are displayed table 1 Panel A:

Photo

Data analysis

The replication package provides already cleaned data in .dta format. We are going to call the data frame fetzer_data.

fetzer_data <- haven::read_dta(
  here::here("ReplicationPackage", "data files", "DISTRICT.dta")
  ) |> 
  dplyr::select(
    code, 
    year, 
    post2010, 
    austerity = totalimpact_finlosswapyr, 
    ukip = pct_votes_UKIP, 
    id, 
    ryr, 
    region = Region
  ) |> 
  filter(!is.na(year)) |> 
  mutate(
    effect = post2010 * austerity # interaction for the analysis
  )

This data is structured at the district-year level. Years considered are displayed from 2000 to 2015 (16 years) by the variable year. Cities are associated to a specific code stored in the variable code.

Replication

As Fetzerâs equation is composed of district and district-year fixed effects, we implement a fixed effect model using feols(). We cluster at district level, such as presented in the do file of the replication package (in district and westminster.do, l. 783).

reg <- fetzer_data |> 
  feols(
  ukip ~ effect ,
  fixef = c("id", "ryr"),
  cluster = ~id,
  fixef.rm = "singleton"
  )
Code 
estimate <- reg |> 
  broom::tidy() |> 
  dplyr::select(estimate)


other <- fetzer_data |>
  mutate(
    treatment_effect = estimate$estimate * austerity
  )|> 
  group_by(year) |>
  mutate(n = n()) |> 
  ungroup() |> 
  reframe(
    `Average treatment effect` = mean(treatment_effect, na.rm = TRUE), 
    `Standard deviation` = sd(treatment_effect, na.rm = TRUE),
    `Local authority districts`=  n
    ) |> 
  distinct() |> 
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(), names_to = "term", values_to = "value") 


list(reg) |> 
  modelsummary::modelsummary(
    gof_omit = "IC|Log|R",

Data generating process

After having shaped the different variables needed for the data generating process (DGP), letâs define it with the function generate_data. We take the values of the means, standard deviations, shapes and scales of the theoretical distributions of \(\lambda_{r,t}\), \(Austerity_i\), and \(VoteUkip_{d,r,t}\).

We added similar information as in Fetzer (2019) for the number of regions, districts, and year. To determine the number of districts per regions, we assumed that each region was composed of the mean number districts of Fetzer, even though there are usually some disparities across regions.

Finally, we defined an epsilonand a beta_0 that is changed so that the ```ukip````variable is following the same distribution as that of Fetzer (2019).

generate_data <- function(# number of districts
                          n_d,
                          # number of regions
                          n_r,
                          # mean number of districts per regions
                          mean_per_region,
                          # number of years
                          n_t,
                          # shape of the region-time fixed effect
                          shape_fe_rt,
                          # scale of the region-time fixed effect
                          scale_fe_rt,
                          # shape of austerity
                          shape_austerity,
                          # scale of austerity
                          scale_austerity,
                          # shape of the error term
                          shape_epsilon,
                          # scale of the error term
                          scale_epsilon,
                          # overall mean
                          beta_0,
                          # estimate
                          beta_1, 
                          sigma_fe_d) {
  
  # We build a region tibble of n_r rows
  region <- tibble(r = 1:n_r)
  # We build a year tibble of n_t rows
  year <- tibble(t = 1:n_t)
  
  # We cross the region and the year tibbles, and add variable that depend on region and time
  crossing_region_year <- crossing(region, year) |>
    mutate(
      # region time fe
      fe_rt = rgamma(n_r * n_t, shape = shape_fe_rt, scale = scale_fe_rt) - beta_0,
      # the index of region - time
      ryr = row_number(), 
      # dummy pre-post period
      post = if_else(t > 9, 1, 0)
    )
  
  # We build a region-district-year tibble
  crossing_region_district_with_year <- region |>
    # Duplicate region by the mean number of districts per region
    uncount(mean_per_region) |>
    # We index each row that represent a single district each
    mutate(d = row_number()) |>
    # We cross this dataset with the year tibble to incorporate the year component
    crossing(year)
  
  # We build a district-specific tibble 
  district <- tibble(d = 1:n_d) |>
    # We add austerity variable as defined with respect to district characteristics
    mutate(
      austerity = rgamma(n_d, shape = shape_austerity, scale = scale_austerity) + shape_austerity * scale_austerity,
      fe_d = rnorm(n_d, 0, sigma_fe_d)
    )
  
  # We build the final dataset by joining the previous tibbles 
  data <- crossing_region_district_with_year |>
    full_join(crossing_region_year) |>
    full_join(district) |>
    # We define variables determined by region, district and year specific characteristics
    mutate(
      # building the epsilon
      total_number_rows =  n(),
      epsilon = rgamma(total_number_rows, shape = shape_epsilon, scale = scale_epsilon),
      # building the interaction term
      effect = post * austerity,
      # ukip vote inferred from previous computations
      ukip = beta_0 + beta_1 * effect + fe_rt + epsilon
    )
}

    scale_epsilon = 1.7,

Now, letâs define the estimation function we named run_estim():

run_estim <- function(data){
  feols(
    fml = ukip ~ effect,
    fixef = c("ryr", "d"), # region-year fe, district fe
    data = data) |> 
    summary() |> 
    broom::tidy(conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95) 
}

Replicate several times

Here is the function we will use to check if the results are similar for more than one experiment.

compute_sim <- function(...){ 
  generate_data(...) %>%
  run_estim() %>%
    cbind(as_tibble(list(...)))
}

We decided to run it for 100 experiments:

Adding categorical variables

Replication

We rebuild the UKIP percentage vote in categorical variables:

fetzer_data <- fetzer_data |>
  mutate(ukip_cat = cut(
    ukip,
    breaks = c(0, 5, 10, 15, 100),
    labels = c("0-5", "5-10", "10-15", ">15"),
    include.lowest = TRUE,
    ordered_result = TRUE
  ))

Here are the results:
